[[Image:Double Centenionalis Magnentius-XR-s4017.jpg|thumb|Centenionalis of [[Magnentius]]]]
The [[bronze]] '''centenionalis''' [[coin]]s (plural: '''centenionales''') were the attempts of [[Constans]] and [[Constantius II]] to reintroduce a large bronze coin between 320 and 340&nbsp;AD, as the [[follis]] had by then shrunk dramatically. The type of coin it was is uncertain, but numismatists have categorized large bronze coins of the above date under this denomination. The centenionalis, however, did not last long. By the end of [[Theodosius I|Theodosius the Great]]'s rule, only [[Constantinian bronzes|smaller varieties of bronze coins]] were minted (AE3 and AE4).<ref>[http://www.deadromans.com/coins/default.htm#Common%20Denominations/ Denominations of Roman coins]</ref>
