{{Underlinked|date=February 2016}}
'''Technoscape''' is a term coined by [[Arjun Appadurai]] in order to describe one of the five dimensions of global cultural flows. The five dimensions consist of ethnoscapes, mediascapes, '''technoscapes''', financescapes, and ideoscapes. The suffix -scape denotes that these terms are perspectival constructs inflected by the historical, linguistic, and political situatedness of different kinds of actors: "[[nation-states]], multinationals, [[Diaspora|diasporic]] communities, as well as subnational groupings and movements".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Appadurai|first1=Arjun|title=Disjuncture and Difference in the Global Economy|date=1990|publisher=John Wiley & Son, Ltd|page=98}}</ref> This can either be religious, political, or economic. In a more specific scope, Technoscape is the movement of technology (mechanical and informational) and the ability to move such technology at rapid speeds.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lechner|first1=Frank|last2=Boli|first2=John|title=The Globalization Reader|date=2015|publisher=John Wiley & Son, Ltd|location=Malden MA|isbn=978-1-118-73355-4|page=97|edition=Fifth}}</ref> This is due to the physical boundaries technology is able to maneuver around.
